14. Nb5 Qb6 15. Nd6+ Kf8 {and now, instead of} 16. Rc1 $5 {
as in F.Cottegnie-R.Cardoso, correspondence 2004,} ({White might play the safer
} 16. c3 $1 dxc3 17. Qxc3 Nd5 18. Qd2 Qe3+ 19. Qxe3 Nxe3 20. Rc1 {when his development lead and open files give him more than enough compensation for the
pawn in the queenless middlegame.})) 7. e5 Nh5 (7... Ng8 8. Bf2 Bb4 9. f4 Ne7
10. Nf3 {leaves Black tangled.}) 8. Bxe7 Qxe7 9. g3 {Preparing to build his
centre with f4. Meanwhile, Black's knight floats in outer space on h5.} O-O 10.
f4 g6 11. Qd2 {White has achieved a wonderful version of the French Defence.}
Ng7 12. Nf3 c5 13. Bh3 {Playing for the f5 pawn break.} Kh7 14. O-O (14. O-O-O
$1 {and then continuing as he did in the game looks grim for Black.}) 14...
cxd4 15. Nxd4 a6 16. Rae1 b5 (16... h5 {only stalls White's plan of g4:} 17.
