give up in the 7 Nf3 line of the Veresov: -- 1. White allows damage to his
pawn structure, isolating his e-pawn and creating a hole on e5. -- 2. White
often must sac his b-pawn to some form of ...Qb6 and ...Qxb2. -- 3. White gets
the open f-file for his attack. This in conjunction with Bc4 and a timely e5
could be deadly for Black, who could implode on f7. -- 4. White in general
gets great piece activity, with a powerful bishop on c4, potentials of Nd4 and
Nf5, and play along the f-file, d-file or b-file if White has sac'ed his
b-pawn. -- 5. You will probably lose most endings if you get there without
doing some damage to Black but as Tarrasch once said: "Before the endgame the
gods have placed the middlegame!"} Qa5 ({Several of my students suggested} 7...
Bd6 {to fortify e5 and play the same strategy Black uses against the Fantasy
line of the Caro-Kann:} 8. Qd2 ({not} 8. dxe5 $6 Nxe5 {
