play this since he has nothing to show for his queenside pawn weaknesses if he
plays it safe with} 8... Bxf6 $6 9. Nxf6+ Qxf6 10. Nf3 {.}) 9. Nf3 {An assessment: -- 1. Black owns the bishop pair; 2. Black's pawns are slightly damaged on
both wings; and 3. Black must solve the question of where to place his king.
There is no obvious safe haven for it anywhere on the board. --- Conclusion:
White stands better.} Qa5+ $6 {
Black's biggest problem is that he doesn't realize he stands worse.} ({
He should play more carefully with} 9... Nd7 10. g3 Bb7 11. Bg2 Qc7 12. O-O {
and then pick a wing for his king.}) 10. Ned2 b4 $6 {
