{Do you have a boogieman in chess? Mine is one of the strongest IMs in the
world, the 2008 US Open Champion Enrico Sevilliano. My dismal lifetime score
before this game was four losses and about 12 draws, despite four or five
winning positions. Even more disconcerting is the fact that Sevilliano's
amiable personality and thug-like chess style don't match at all. Playing
Enrico is exactly like having your mild-mannered and soft-spoken neighbour
drop in for a cup of tea, and then immediately after the tea, put a knife to
your throat and issue demands for your wallet!} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 d5 3. Bg5 e6
4. e4 Bb4 5. exd5 {The day before this game was played, John Emms emailed me
and suggested the Lasker Variation against the McCutcheon French for this book.
He reasoned that it bypasses the heavily-analysed lines and contains a drop of
poison.} ({I spent the entire morning of the previous day studying the Lasker
line, which certainly threw my opponent, who seemed to only be familiar with
mainlines like} 5. e5 h6 6. Bd2 ({and} 6. Be3 $5 {. If you decide to play the
mainline, make sure you investigate it deeply before testing it out over the
board.})) 5... exd5 {It's an Exchange French, but on our terms. French players
always have a favourite aggressive arrangement against the Exchange lines. For
instance, they often favour ...Nc6, ...Bd6, ...Nge7, ...Bg4, ...Qd7 and castle
queenside. By playing a late exchange line, we deny French players their
cherished set-ups.} ({Next game we look at} 5... Qxd5 {.}) 6. Bd3 ({
In this position, I also like the line} 6. Qf3 c6 7. Bd3 Nbd7 (7... h6 $6 {
looks untrustworthy after} 8. Bxf6 Qxf6 9. Qxf6 gxf6 {when Black's bishop pair
doesn't fully compensate for the damaged structure, K.Spraggett-A.David, Metz
2009}) 8. Nge2 O-O 9. O-O-O Be7 {, as in L.Fressinet-Y.Pelletier, Istanbul
Olympiad 2000. Let's assess: it's an opposite wings attack position, but Black
felt the need to waste a precious tempo with his last move because the bishop
on b4 gets in the way of his pawn storm.} ({
He can also save the tempo by exchanging for the knight on c3,} 9... Bxc3 10.
Nxc3 b5 {, but I don't like Black here either. White has the bishop pair and
controls the dark squares. It's doubtful Black will make something tangible
happen from his queenside attack.})) 6... c5 $6 {Sevilliano excels in open
games, but this move is over-enthusiastic and he simply falls behind in
development.} ({He should behave himself and castle:} 6... O-O 7. Nge2 Bg4 $6 (
{better is} 7... c6) 8. O-O c6 9. f3 Bh5 10. Nf4 $1 Bg6 11. Nxg6 hxg6 12. f4 $1
Be7 13. f5 {with the bishop pair and attacking chances, T.Bromann-J.Sorensen,
Danish League 2009.}) 7. dxc5 d4 8. a3 Bxc5 $2 {Only making matters worse.} ({
He should go for} 8... Bxc3+ 9. bxc3 dxc3 10. Ne2 O-O 11. O-O Nbd7 12. c6 bxc6
13. Nxc3 {when White's bishops are meaningful in the open position, but it
isn't the end of the world for Black.}) 9. Ne4 Be7 10. Bxf6 Bxf6 11. Nxf6+ $6 {
Unlike my opponent, I just don't have the open-game gene. I tend to over-finesse
and try to control some weak square when I should be going after the opponent
with a meat axe! I remember one exasperated ICC kibitzer offering me this
piece of constructive criticism after I had botched a similar game: "It's
called the initiative. You ought to try it sometime! Idiot!!"} ({
Here I should play} 11. Qh5 $1 g6 12. Qh6 {
, but I had a blind spot and missed this obvious move. After} Bf5 13. Nf3 {
Black is in big trouble.}) 11... Qxf6 12. Qf3 Qb6 {The ending would be clearly
in White's favour. I would simply pile on the weak d4-pawn.} 13. O-O-O O-O 14.
Ne2 Nc6 15. Kb1 $6 ({I considered and then rejected the stronger} 15. Be4 $1 {:
} -- ({. I was unjustifiably afraid of} 15... Ne5 {, but then} 16. Qh5 (16.
Bxh7+ $4 {fails miserably to} Kxh7 17. Qh5+ Qh6+ {
and oops, it's a check and I don't get my piece back!}) 16... f5 17. Nxd4 $1
fxe4 18. Qxe5 Rxf2 19. Qe8+ Rf8 20. Qxe4 {with an extra pawn.}) (15... Bd7 16.
Qd3 $1 {(sigh... I missed this one too)} g6 17. Nxd4 {
and Black doesn't have sufficient compensation for the pawn.})) 15... Be6 16.
Nf4 Rae8 17. Rhe1 Qc5 $2 {I couldn't believe my eyes! My opponent misses a
simple double-attack. At this point, I felt like a homeless and destitute man,
who, rummaging through the trash, finds a 7-carat diamond! I had a feeling my
Sevilliano curse was about to end.} 18. Nxe6 fxe6 19. Qh3 $1 {
Enrico said he totally forgot about this move, which wins a pawn.} g6 20. Rxe6
Rxe6 21. Qxe6+ Kg7 22. f3 Ne5 23. Re1 {I just wanted to simplify.} ({Rybka says
} 23. Be4 $1 {is very strong. By now the old paranoia had kicked in and I was
wondering just how I would bungle this one.}) 23... Nxd3 24. cxd3 Rf7 25. Qe5+
{A critical point. I was certain the rook ending was a win for White.} ({
If I were braver I could also play for an attack with} 25. Re5 Qc7 26. h4 {.})
25... Qxe5 26. Rxe5 {Black is busted in the rook ending. My plan: -- 1. Tie
him down to his weak d4-pawn; -- 2. Centralize my king; -- 3. Play Rb5 and
force ...b6; -- 4. Push my queenside pawns to a4 and b5 to fix another
potential target on a7; and -- 5. Slowly create a passed pawn on the kingside
with my majority.} Rd7 27. Kc2 Kf6 28. f4 h5 ({The subtle} 28... h6 $1 {
intending ...g5 pretty much forces White to create a weakness with the
concession} 29. h4 h5 {. Now Black has ...Kf5 and ...Kg4 in case White's rook
wanders off the fifth rank. Here, though, is White's winning technique:} 30.
Kd2 Rd6 31. Rb5 $1 Rd7 32. a4 Ke6 33. a5 Kf6 34. b4 Ke6 35. Ke2 Kf6 36. Kf3 Re7
37. Kf2 Rd7 38. Rc5 Kf7 39. Kf3 Kf6 40. Ke4 Re7+ 41. Kxd4 Re2 42. Rc7 Rxg2 43.
Rxb7 {and the race will not even be close.}) 29. g3 ({White shouldn't lock with
} 29. h4 {if he has a choice.}) 29... Rd6 30. Rb5 $1 {As in the Vaganian-Adamski game from Chapter Two, White uses the fifth rank effectively here to create
weaknesses and box in Black's king.} b6 ({
The alternative is to defend passively with} 30... Rd7 {.}) 31. Kd2 Rd7 32. a4
Rd6 33. b4 Rd7 34. Re5 h4 $6 {This aggression makes White's task easier. Now
his h-pawn is separated and weak.} 35. g4 h3 36. g5+ {Bottling up his king.}
Kf7 37. b5 {To fix an additional target on a7.} Kf8 38. Re4 $1 {
There is no good defence to Ke2, Kf3, Kg4 and Kxh4.} Kf7 39. Ke2 Rc7 40. Kf3
Rc2 41. Kg3 Rg2+ 42. Kxh3 Rg1 43. Kh4 Rg2 44. Rxd4 {I confess to a bit of
bravado on my part since I knew I was winning anyway and was happy to offer
the h2-pawn to free my king. Shantideva, a 7th Century Buddhist monk,
correctly observed: "When they find a dying serpent, even crows behave like
soaring eagles!"} Ke6 45. Rd8 $1 {Intending 46 Rf8 and Rf6+. The game is over.
Only the hope based on the happy memories of my previous incompetence in past
games kept my opponent playing on!} Rxh2+ ({The main idea behind 45 Rd8 is} 
45... Kf5 $2 46. Rf8+ Ke6 47. Rf6+ {.}) 46. Kg4 Rg2+ 47. Kf3 Ra2 48. Rf8 {
The g-pawn falls, and with it all of Black's hopes. White is too far ahead in
the race.} Rxa4 49. Rf6+ Ke7 50. Rxg6 Ra5 51. Rg7+ Ke6 52. Ke4 Rxb5 53. f5+ Kd6
(53... Rxf5 $4 {drops the rook to} 54. Rg6+ {.}) 54. Rxa7 {It's a good thing
chess pieces can't become overweight! The perpetually-hungry pig eats his fill
at the trough.} Rb1 55. g6 Rg1 56. g7 {. 57 f6 followed by Ra8 wins. Free at
last, free at last! The curse ends. --- Summary: If Black responds to the
Lasker line of the McCutcheon with 5...exd5, he ends up in an Exchange French,
unable to enter his favourite set-up, and with his bishop possibly misplaced
on b4.} 1-0

