The threat of 11...c4 forces White to break the central tension.} ({Instead,} 
10... Nd5 11. dxc5 Nxe3 12. Qxe3 Bxc5 13. Qg5 g6 ({perhaps Black should risk} 
13... O-O 14. Qh4 h6 15. Rhe1) 14. h4 Be7 15. Qe3 Bd7 16. Kb1 O-O-O 17. Ne5 Bc5
18. Qe2 Be8 19. h5 {left White with a pull, despite Black's bishop pair in C.Peptan-A.Maric, Budva 2003.}) 11. dxc5 Bxc5 12. Bxc5 ({After} 12. Bg5 Bb7 13.
Ne5 (13. Bxf6 $1) 13... Bd6 14. f4 $2 (14. Bxf6 gxf6 15. Ng4) 14... Nd5 $1 {
White found it awkward to deal with the undermining threat of ...h6 in A.
Shirov-Y.Drozdovskij, Mainz (rapid) 2007.}) 12... Qxc5 13. Ne5 Bb7 14. Rhe1 O-O
{An instructive moment. I showed this position to several students and asked
for an assessment. Nearly every one of them gave Black the thumbs up with
statements like: "Black's attack is well underway, while White's hasn't
started." Or, "Black is clearly faster with the open c-file." --- The truth is,
White's attack is more potent. First of all, because Black's knight will be
ejected with tempo. Second, Qe4! creates serious weakness in Black's kingside
structure. Black's only plan of attack lies in a pawn storm with ...b4, ...a5,
...a4 and probably ...a3, but this simply takes too long.} 15. g4 $1 {
Impulsive, committal, and very powerful! --- White does weaken the f4-square,
but more importantly he doesn't lose a tempo wasting a move with f2-f4. He
threatens 16 g5, followed by (after 16...Nd5) Qe4, Ng4, Nf6+ and Qh4 with a
winning attack.} Qb4 $1 {Fighting for the f4-square and sidestepping White's
attacking ideas based on Qe4.} ({
If Black doesn't take swift measures and develops calmly with} 15... Rad8 $2 {
, he gets swept away by the tide of the attack:} 16. g5 Nd5 17. Qe4 g6 18. Ng4
$1 {(exploiting the punctured dark squares; one threat is Qe5 and Nh6 mate)}
Nb4 19. Nf6+ Kg7 20. Qh4 h5 21. gxh6+ Kh8 22. Nd7 $1 {
with a crushing double threat.}) 16. h4 Nd5 17. Qe4 $1 {Great judgement, and
also the sign of flexibility. White hasn't signed a legally-binding contract
which stipulates he must checkmate at any cost. He can also play for the
superior ending, as he has three factors in his favour: a pin on the d5-knight,
a space advantage and the superior pawn majority.} Qxe4 ({
I would have tried my luck in the line} 17... f5 $5 18. Qxb4 Nxb4 19. gxf5
Nxd3+ 20. Nxd3 Bf3 21. Rd2 exf5 22. Re3 Bg4 23. Nf4 {
, even though the knight is superior to the bishop.}) 18. Bxe4 Rfd8 $2 {
The wrong plan. Doubling rooks on the d-file allows White to mirror this plan.
Black begins to get tangled on two pins, lateral and horizontal, on the
d5-knight.} ({Alternatively:} 18... f6 $2 19. Nd7 Rfe8 20. Bxd5 $1 Bxd5 21. Nb6
Rad8 22. Nxd5 exd5 23. Rxe8+ Rxe8 24. Rxd5 {with good chances of conversion
