{I used to play Levon Aronian when he was a teenage IM on the ICC around the
time this game was played. He had such an unassuming, stodgy style (like
Reshevsky), that it never occurred to me that just a few years later he would
be a contender ranked in the top five players in the world.} 1. d4 d5 2. Nc3 c5
3. e4 $1 {
The Albin Counter-Gambit, but a full move up since it's White who plays it.}
cxd4 $6 {Black declines the gambit and fires back with the offer of a dubious
one himself.} ({
I think the best route for Black in this position is to decline the gambit with
} 3... Nf6 $1 4. e5 {and then:} -- (4... Ne4 5. Nxe4 dxe4 6. d5 Qc7 7. Bf4 g5
$1 8. Bg3 Bg7 9. Qh5 Bxe5 10. O-O-O $1 ({sidestepping} 10. Qxg5 Qa5+ $1) 10...
Bf4+ 11. Kb1 Nd7 {and now, instead of the} 12. Qh6 $2 {
of G.Portisch-C.Csiszar, Zalaegerszeg 1992,} (12. Qxg5 $1 {
leaves White slightly better.})) (4... Nfd7 {transposes to a line in the
Alekhine, which comes from the order 1 e4 Nf6 2 Nc3 d5 3 e5 Nfd7 4 d4 c5. Now}
5. e6 $5 fxe6 6. Nf3 {was seen in J.Hector-M.Konopka, German League 1997, and
gives White reasonable compensation for the pawn, with his control over e5 and
Black's clogged situation with both bishops.})) ({
Next game we'll look at Black's third option,} 3... dxe4 {.}) 4. Qxd4 Nc6 $1 ({
Obligatory, since} 4... dxe4 $2 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 6. Bf4 {led to an ending where
Black's king was in real peril in the game H.Mayerhofer-I.Somerlik, Hrabyne
1995.}) 5. Qxd5 Bd7 {This is the kind of shaky gambit you encounter at chess
clubs all over the world. You know in your heart that your opponent's sac
shouldn't work, but the reality is that you must endure his initiative for the
next 20 moves or so. Watch how Aronian patiently rebuffs his opponent's
attempts to make something concrete with his initiative.} 6. Nf3 Nf6 7. Qd1 $1
{A psychologically difficult move to make, but a good one. Most players regard
the retreat of an already developed piece back to its original square as a
kind of defeat. However, keeping the queen 'developed' elsewhere simply hands
Black a convenient target for his pieces. A parallel can be made between
Aronian's move and a line of the French: 1 e4 e6 2 d4 d5 3 Nc3 Bb4 4 e5 b6 5
Qg4 Bf8!. There the bishop returns to its place of birth to avoid weakening or
moving the king.} e5 8. Bd3 $1 ({Aronian consolidates, avoiding the sharper} 8.
Bc4 {.}) 8... Bb4 9. Bd2 O-O 10. h3 $1 {Aronian's careful play demonstrates
that Black has only fishing chances for the pawn.} Re8 11. Ne2 $1 {
Principle: trade down when ahead in material.} Bxd2+ 12. Qxd2 Qb6 13. c3 Rad8
14. Qc2 Rc8 15. Qb3 Qa5 16. O-O Be6 {It looks like Black is getting somewhere
kicking White around, but in reality he is building a castle in the sky since
White's position doesn't deteriorate in any way. It goes against our human
nature to allow the opponent to bully us for this long. See though how Aronian
humbly forebears the insults and turns the other cheek in response to his
opponent's shoving, patiently waiting for his turn to be in control. This
patience is often misinterpreted as lethargy or cowardice by players on the
club level. It's not, and I remind them to re-read the story of the tortoise
and the hare we read as children!} 17. Qc2 $1 {
He isn't afraid of ghosts on the c-file.} b5 ({Naturally,} 17... Nb4 $4 {
fails to the simple} 18. cxb4 $1 Rxc2 19. bxa5 {, winning a piece.}) 18. Ng5
Bc4 19. Nf3 $1 {I discovered long ago that it annoys opponents if I repeat a
position twice, and then pull the rug out from under them, refusing to repeat
a third time. Perhaps Aronian's motives for repetition were not as
Machiavellian as mine, and he simply repeated to get closer to the move 40
mark and avoid time trouble.} Rcd8 ({Realizing that White may just be toying
with him and would most certainly have avoided the draw after} 19... Be6 20. b4
$1 Qb6 21. Rfb1 {with a4 to follow.}) 20. Bxc4 bxc4 21. b4 cxb3 ({After} 21...
Qc7 22. Rfd1 {Black has zip for the pawn.}) 22. axb3 {White removed the air
out of Black's initiative with carefully sustained defence. Watch how he keeps
improving his game, little by little.} Qb6 23. Ra4 a6 24. Nd2 $1 {
Protecting b3 and keeping the possibility of c4 as a nice perch for the knight.
} Qc5 25. Nc4 ({Avoiding the silly trap} 25. Rxa6 $4 Nb4 {.}) 25... a5 26. Rfa1
{The initiative swings over to White, who retains his extra pawn and now eyes
a new target on a5.} Ra8 27. Nc1 $1 {Incremental adjustments. See how he
slowly brings all his pieces into play? The knight wasn't doing much on e2,
but on c1 it covers b3 and prepares to enter the fight from d3.} Red8 28. Ne3
Qd6 $2 {Black is under the impression that he still has the initiative and
misses White's threat.} ({However, if} 28... Rab8 29. Rc4 Qb5 30. Nd3 $1 Nxe4
31. Nxe5 $1 Nxe5 32. Rxe4 {White stays up a pawn.}) 29. b4 $1 {
Another one bites the dust!} Rac8 ({Realizing the futility of} 29... Qc7 30.
Nb3 {.}) 30. bxa5 Nd4 31. Qb2 {Even two pawns up, Aronian doesn't mind dancing
to his opponent's tune for a while longer.} Rb8 32. Qa2 Ne6 33. Nb3 Qd3 $6 ({
His position is still busted after the superior} 33... Qa6 {.}) 34. a6 $1 {
The c3-pawn doesn't matter. The advancing a-pawn paralyses Black.} Qxc3 35. a7
Rxb3 (35... Ra8 36. Rc4 $1 Qd3 37. Rd1 {traps the queen in mid-board.}) 36. Rc4
{. I realize this low-key game isn't the most exciting in the book, but it's
instructive. In books and magazines it's always the attackers who get all the
attention and glory. In real life patient defenders win just as often. ---
Summary: Declining the Reversed Albin with 3...Nf6! looks like Black's best
route to equality.} 1-0

