1. d4 f5 2. Nc3 {. Unlike some of the earlier chapters in this book where your
author suggests some of the more dubious Veresov lines with a distinctively
apologetic tone, in this chapter I can confidently tell you that the Veresov
is one of the best methods of meeting Dutch. With 2 Nc3! our goal is simple:
blast open with e4! When it happens, Black often finds himself unprepared and
behind in development. Dutch players have three choices:} -- ({
Black meets the Veresov approach with a Stonewall Dutch Structure,} 2... Nf6 3.
Bg5 d5 {, when our plan of Qd2, f3 and playing for e4 looks effective.}) ({
Black goes} 2... Nf6 3. Bg5 e6 {and allows White the e4 break. After} 4. e4
fxe4 5. Nxe4 {Black falls behind in space and development. I suggest a
promising pawn sac line where White stands better whether Black accepts or
declines.}) ({
Black meets the Veresov with a Leningrad Dutch/Stonewall hybrid formation,} 
2... d5 3. Bg5 g6 {. Black's problem is, he really doesn't want to play ...d5,
but he must. Otherwise, White has the killer idea h4-h5!, sac the exchange on
h5 and follow with e4! This gives White a murderous attack, so Black is
virtually forced into the weakening ...d5 move. Our normal plan f3, Qd2,
possibly castle queenside, and force e4 also works very well here. Another
wonderful benefit is that Leningrad players are prodded into a Stonewall
structure, which they are not used to and usually bungle with great
consistency!}) *

