{As I write this, India's beloved son, Anand, faces the much-despised Topalov
for the World Championship title. IM Jack Peters recently sent all the titled
players in Southern California a poll asking who would win the match.
Logically, I felt Topalov must have the edge due to his youth. As I typed my
e-mail response to Jack, I found my fingers typing the following on their on
volition: "Hi Jack, Anand by a point! Best wishes, Cy." As a card-carrying
member of the COA (Church of Anand) there is no way I am going to vote against
our messiah! (Postscript: Prepare the elephants for the parade. Anand wins!)} 
1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Bg5 {Neither Pirc nor Modern discourages us
from our favourite set-up. It's worth quoting again Modern specialist GM Nigel
Davies' view of this line in his 'Starting Out: The Modern': "In my opinion
the Byrne System with 3 Nc3 and 4 Bg5 is one of the most dangerous at White's
disposal, yet it tends to crop up surprisingly little in practice."} Bg7 5. Qd2
h6 ({Black may opt to avoid chasing down the bishop with} 5... c6 6. f4 b5 7.
Bd3 O-O 8. Nf3 Bg4 9. O-O {, as in M.Kobalia-B.Rimawi, Amman 2006, but White's
position looks rather easy to play: build up on the kingside and play for mate.
His centre remains quite stable for an Austrian-style position of the Pirc,
and this factor favours him.}) 6. Bh4 g5 {Black insists on chasing down the
bishop and punishing White by depriving him of the bishop pair. However,
nothing in life is free. White's compensation: -- 1. hxg3 opens the h-file for
his attack; -- 2. If Black doesn't take the bishop right away, then he may be
vulnerable to h4 ideas; -- 3. White plays a knight to e2 and then prises open
with f4; and -- 4. White plays a knight to e2 and may recapture on g3 with a
knight, which then has access to h5. This in turn may drive Black's
fianchettoed bishop off the a1-h8 diagonal.} 7. Bg3 Nh5 8. O-O-O Nc6 ({Others:
} 8... Nd7 9. e5 $1 {
(a promising pawn sac; always be on the lookout for this move)} Nxg3 10. hxg3
dxe5 $6 ({Black should decline with} 10... Nb6) 11. dxe5 Bxe5 12. f4 $1 gxf4
13. gxf4 Bg7 14. Rh3 $1 c6 15. Rg3 Bf6 16. Ne4 Qb6 17. Rb3 Qc7 18. Nh3 Bg7 19.
Rg3 Kf8 20. Nc5 $1 Qd6 {
was S.Tiviakov-M.Mohammed Abdul, Bhubaneswar 2009, and now} 21. Qa5 $1 {
ends the game.}) (8... Nxg3 9. hxg3 Nc6 10. Bb5 $1 a6 11. Bxc6+ bxc6 12. f4
gxf4 13. gxf4 Bg4 14. Nf3 Qb8 15. e5 {was C.Balogh-T.Nyback, Budapest 2002.
You already know how I feel about knights, so you won't be surprised when I
tell you I prefer White's space over Black's bishop pair.}) 9. Qe3 $5 {
Moving the queen off the d-file gets Black nervous about e5 ideas.} ({Instead,
} 9. Bb5 Bd7 10. Nge2 e6 11. Kb1 Qe7 12. d5 Ne5 13. Bxe5 Bxe5 14. Bxd7+ Qxd7
15. h4 g4 16. Qe3 $1 {left Black in a quandary about where to place his king,
J.Van der Wiel-T.Chapman, Hoogeveen 2008.}) 9... Bd7 10. Nge2 e6 {
This flexible move is played the most.} ({Black may consider the more forcing} 
10... e5 11. dxe5 Nxg3 12. hxg3 Nxe5 13. Nd4 Ng4 14. Qd2 $6 (14. Qe2 $1 {
intending f3 is an improvement and secures the advantage}) 14... Qf6 $1 15. f3
Qxd4 $1 16. Qxd4 Bxd4 17. Rxd4 Ne5 {
and Black equalized in M.Ruimy-G.Wicklund Hansen, correspondence 2002.}) 11. h4
Qe7 ({Alternatively:} 11... Qf6 12. e5 $1 dxe5 13. dxe5 Qe7 (13... Nxe5 14.
hxg5 hxg5 15. Ne4 Qf5 16. Rxd7 $1 Nxd7 17. Bxc7 {
offers terrific compensation for the exchange}) 14. Bh2 Qb4 {
and now instead of the} 15. g4 $5 {of A.Shabalov-E.Vovsha, Connecticut 2002,} (
15. a3 $1 Qb6 16. Qf3 {looks promising for White.})) (11... Nxg3 12. Nxg3 Rg8 (
{after} 12... gxh4 $5 13. Nh5 Bxd4 14. Rxd4 Qg5 15. Rd2 Qxh5 16. Nb5 Kd8 17. f4
a6 18. Nc3 Ke7 {White's attacking chances compensate for the material}) 13. Nh5
