: for example,} Rb8 28. Bb5 Rb7 29. Bc6 Bc8 30. Bd8 $1 Kb8 31. Bxb7 Bxb7 32.
Nc6+ Kc8 33. Nxa7+ Kb8 34. Bxc7+ Kxc7 35. Nb5+ {wins.}) 27... Ng6 28. Ba6 Nxh4
29. Bxc8 Rxc8 30. Rxh4 {The complications have ended and White has a technical
win. Nobody mops up better than Leko in such positions: -- 1. White is a clean
pawn up; -- 2. His knight is superior to Black's bishop; -- 3. Black must
cover light-squared weaknesses on the queenside; and -- 4. Black must nurse a
weak h-pawn.} Kb7 31. a3 Rg8 32. Ne2 $1 Qg5 33. Rh5 $1 Qe7 ({
No choice but to hand over h6 since} 33... Qg6 $2 34. Nf4 Qh7 35. Qf6 {
loses it under even worse circumstances.}) 34. Rxh6 f5 $1 {
Black eliminates his last weakness, but he can't overcome the two-pawn deficit.
} 35. gxf5 Bxf5 36. Nd4 Bd7 37. Ne6 Bc8 38. f4 Rg4 39. Qc6+ Kb8 40. Rh8 ({
