1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 Nbd7 {I admit to a canine-like affection for this
line, the Black Lion, a Philidor coming out of a Pirc move order. Most
Philidorians (by now you probably have realized my strange compulsion for
making up random words!) are positional players who revel in behind-the-lines
manoeuvring games. We do our best to avoid this with our next move!} 4. g4 $1 {
The Lion's Mouth. As a Lion player on the black side, this is the one line
which makes me very uneasy! White lunges forward and threatens to deport the
knight back to g8 next move with 5 g5.} h6 {Prudent. Black slows down g5.} ({
We will also examine} 4... e5 $6 {in due course.}) 5. h3 e5 ({
I sometimes hit back in Sicilian style with} 5... c5 {, and after} 6. Nge2 b5
$5 7. Nxb5 Nxe4 8. Bg2 Bb7 9. O-O a6 10. Nbc3 Nxc3 11. bxc3 Bxg2 12. Kxg2 g6
13. dxc5 Nxc5 14. Qd4 Rg8 15. Rb1 Bg7 16. Qd5 Rc8 {White's piece activity and
Black's superior pawn structure balance each other out, M.Parligras-C.Lakdawala, Internet blitz 2010.}) 6. Nge2 c6 (6... b5 $5 {
is also possible, but after} 7. a3 c6 8. Bg2 Be7 9. f4 Bb7 10. O-O {in M.Prusikin-R.Forster, Swiss League 2008, White had an ominous kingside build-up. Black
would be very brave or very stupid to castle into this one!}) 7. a4 {
Slowing down Black's queenside expansion.} a6 ({Others:} 7... Be7 8. Bg2 g5 $6
{(White benefits more from f5 than Black from f4)} 9. Ng3 Nf8 10. Nf5 Ng6 11.
Be3 Bxf5 12. exf5 Nh4 13. O-O Qc7 14. Bh1 h5 15. d5 $1 {with a clear strategic
advantage for White. This prompted Akobian to sac soon with} hxg4 16. hxg4 Qd7
17. a5 c5 18. Ne4 Nxf5 $6 19. Nxf6+ Bxf6 20. gxf5 Qxf5 21. Bg2 {, but Black
didn't achieve sufficient comp for the piece in S.Kudrin-V.Akobian, Tulsa 2008.
}) (7... b6 {slowly preparing ...a6, ...Rb8 and ...b5 is also possible. Then}
8. Be3 Bb7 9. Bg2 Qc7 10. O-O a6 11. Qd2 {
gave White quite a harmonious set-up in P.Herb-M.Schrepp, German League 1998.})
({Next game we see} 7... a5 {.}) 8. Bg2 Rb8 9. a5 b5 {
He seeks activity at the cost of slightly weakening his a-pawn.} 10. axb6 Qxb6
11. b3 Be7 12. Be3 Qc7 13. Ng3 g6 {This is one of Black's biggest problems in
this line. He almost always needs to weaken with ...g6 to keep a white knight
out of f5.} 14. Qd2 h5 $1 {This and his next two moves begin a strategic plan
to undermine White's space on the kingside and generate counterplay.} 15. g5
Nh7 16. h4 f6 $1 17. gxf6 Ndxf6 18. f3 O-O 19. Nge2 {
Neither king looks terribly safe!} Rf7 20. Qd3 $1 {A strong prophylactic move:
-- 1. Spraggett reasons that Black's best shot at counterplay lies in
achieving the ...d5 break; -- 2. The white queen lies in wait for that move
ready to pounce on g6 if it is ever played; -- 3. The queen hits a6. Why is
this important? Because White plans Bh3! and eventually swaps on c8, removing
Black's defender of a6; and -- 4. Should Black dodge the exchange with
something like ...Bb7, then White takes control over the powerful h3-c8
diagonal.} Nf8 21. Bh3 $1 N6d7 22. f4 $1 {Ignoring the threat to his h-pawn.}
exd4 {If he is going to be attacked then at least be paid for it with a pawn!}
({I would grab it with} 22... Bxh4+ 23. Kd2 exd4 24. Bxd4 Bf6 25. Qg3 {.}) 23.
Bxd4 Nc5 $6 {Again, I would grab the h-pawn and dare White to mate me.} 24.
Bxc5 $1 ({Stronger than} 24. Qg3 Bxh3 25. Rxh3 Nce6 26. Bf2 Kh7 27. O-O-O Bf6 {
.}) 24... dxc5 25. Bxc8 Rxc8 26. e5 $1 {Multi-purpose: -- 1. Opening a pathway
to g6; -- 2. Clearing e4 for a knight; and -- 3. Blunting Black's dark-squared
bishop along the long diagonal.} Rd8 27. Qxa6 $5 {Many players wouldn't bother
with such a pawn and allow themselves to get distracted from the attack on the
black king. Kevin Spraggett was the only titled player in Montreal, where I
grew up. I used to play in a Friday night blitz tournament with him
participating. In my many battles (as a 15-year old versus the then IM
Spraggett!) I noticed just how unapologetically greedy he was! This left a
deep impression on me, and to this day I follow my teacher's path and play
like an avaricious Wall Street banker!} ({The more noble among us would play} 
27. Qe4 {.}) 27... Ne6 28. O-O $1 {
White plans to win, not on attack, but on superior pawn structure.} Nd4 ({
He rejects} 28... Bxh4 29. Ne4 Be7 30. Qc4 Qd7 {.}) 29. Nxd4 Rxd4 30. Ne2 Qd7
$1 31. Rf2 Rd1+ 32. Rxd1 Qxd1+ 33. Kh2 Qe1 34. Kg2 Bxh4 35. Rf1 Qd2 36. Qc4 {
The initiative is with Black; the structure with White.} Kg7 {He avoids a
queen trade and ends up swapping a few moves later under worse circumstances.}
({Black is slightly worse in the ending after} 36... Qd5+ $1 37. Qxd5 cxd5 38.
Ra1 {, but my feeling is that he should hold it.}) 37. Qe4 Qd5 38. Nc3 {
Too late. Now Black must live with a compromised structure.} Qxe4+ $2 {
A bitter wind follows this decision to meekly submit to a difficult ending.} ({
Better to repeat with} 38... Qd2+ {and see how White proceeds.}) 39. Nxe4 Rd7
40. Kf3 Be7 41. Ra1 {This is going to be rough for Black, as his pawns stink
and the white knight, with the powerful outpost on e4, outguns Black's bishop.
Moreover, White's rook controls the a-file and is ready to go after the
queenside pawns and, basically, Black looks busted.} Kf7 42. Ra6 Rd1 ({
If Black goes passive with} 42... Rc7 {then White makes progress with} 43. Ra8
Ke6 44. Rh8 $1 {.}) 43. Rxc6 Rf1+ 44. Ke3 Re1+ 45. Kd3 Rd1+ 46. Ke2 Rc1 47. e6+
$1 Kf8 48. Rc8+ Kg7 49. Re8 $1 Bf6 50. Kd2 Rf1 51. e7 $1 {
The e-pawn costs Black a piece.} h4 $4 (51... Bxe7 52. Rxe7+ Kf8 53. Rc7 Rxf4
54. Nxc5 {and Black's passers are halted with ease.}) 52. Rg8+ {. --- Summary:
As a Lion player, out of all of White's options 4 g4 scares me the most.} 1-0

