Bc4 22. Re1 Nf6 23. Nf5 {Black still had to be careful of White's kingside
build-up in R.Damaso-A.Strikovic, Internet (blitz) 2004.}) 9. O-O g6 10. Be3
Bg7 {Be aware that the Philidor is a flexible formation and the resulting
positions may look more like Pirc than traditional Philidor positions with a
bishop on e7. Let's assess: -- 1. After Qd2, Black won't be able to castle
without playing ...h5 or ...g5; -- 2. White is ready for f4; and -- 3. Black's
king is somewhat stuck and faces danger whichever direction he goes. ---
Conclusion: Black stands worse. If so, then the question of where Black went
wrong arises. As a Philidor player, I sometimes wonder if the entire opening
is just inherently in White's favour. Of course, don't tell this to those guys
who wrote those Lion books or I will get some angry mail in response!} 11. Qd2
b6 $2 {Strategically suspect. A d5 push weakens Black's b5-square.} ({
He should play} 11... h5 $1 12. g5 Nh7 13. Rad1 O-O {.}) 12. f4 ({
It's not bad to maintain the tension, but} 12. d5 $1 {
, striking at the heart of Black's problems, also favours White after} cxd5 13.
Nb5 Qb8 14. f4 $1 {. If then} d4 $6 {White blows open the centre with} 15. Bxd4
exd4 16. Nexd4 $1 Bb7 17. e5 $1 O-O 18. exf6 Nxf6 19. Nc6 Bxc6 20. Bxc6 Ra6 21.
Rae1 {when Black is in deep trouble, with a pawn about to fall and a totally
immobilized rook on a6.}) 12... Ba6 13. Rf2 O-O-O $1 {
I don't blame him. The kingside looks distinctly unsafe.} 14. fxe5 dxe5 15. d5
$1 c5 $2 {Strategic suicide.} ({He had to maintain the tension with} 15... Nc5
$1 16. Bxc5 bxc5 17. Qe3 Rhe8 18. Raf1 Rd6 19. Qxc5 cxd5 20. Qxc7+ Kxc7 21.
exd5 e4 22. Nb5+ Bxb5 23. axb5 e3 24. Rf4 Kb6 25. c4 Nd7 $1 26. b3 Bf6 {
when, despite White's three connected passers, Black has compensation for the
pawn in the form of: -- 1. A grip on the dark squares; -- 2. An active king,
which may infiltrate if a few more pieces come off the board; and -- 3. A
strong blockade on c5 and d6. --- Still, Rybka gives White the edge.}) 16. Ng3
Nb8 17. Bf1 $1 {
Handing out the eviction notice to Black to clear out of the light squares.} h5
$2 {A blunder, losing material.} ({Black should play} 17... Ne8 18. Bxa6+ Nxa6
19. Nb5 Qd7 20. Qe2 Kb7 21. c3 {with an awful, but materially equal position.})
18. Bxa6+ Nxa6 19. Bg5 $1 h4 20. Nf1 Qe7 21. Ne3 Nc7 22. Raf1 Nce8 {What a tang
led picture of hopelessness. Black's forces strain to cover their endangered
comrade on f6. Meanwhile, White is left unopposed in the other sector and does
as he pleases.} 23. Qe2 $1 {
Running roughshod through the light squares on the queenside.} ({
