pawn remains on c2 rather than c4. Other differences and similarities? -- 1.
White saves a tempo on c4. -- 2. In a regular Benoni, Black normally trades
his e-pawn for White's c-pawn. This creates queenside versus kingside pawn
majorities and a potentially sharper game. In the Schmid Benoni, the structure
remains more symmetrical with White holding more space due to his d5 wedge. --
3. Just as in the Benoni proper, White mostly plays for the generally more
effective e5 pawn break while Black plays for the ...b5 break; -- 4. Black
hasn't played ...e6 yet and may even later play the pawn to e5. If and when
Black plays ...e6, White must make a crucial decision to capture on e6, which
you play if you feel you can pressure his backward pawn on d6. However, retain
the central pawn tension if you feel that Black will eventually achieve the
freeing ...d5 break after the exchange on e6.} ({Instead,} 5... a6 {stops our next move but also ruins Black's normal plan of ...Na6-c7 to slowly prepare the
...b5 pawn break. After} 6. a4 Nf6 7. Be2 O-O 8. O-O Bg4 9. Nd2 $5 ({
White can also play for the bishops:} 9. Re1 Bxf3 10. Bxf3) 9... Bxe2 10. Qxe2
Nbd7 11. Nc4 Nb6 12. Ne3 $1 {
(the side with space should keep pieces on the board)} Re8 13. Rd1 $1 {
(discouraging the ...e6 break)} Qc7 14. f3 Rad8 15. a5 Nc8 16. Nc4 Nd7 17. Bf4
Na7 18. Na4 Nb5 {Black found himself without much counterplay against White's
space plus in U.Andersson-A.Zapata, Wijk aan Zee 1987.}) 6. Bb5+ {
This annoying check throws Black a bit out of sync.} Nbd7 {The most natural
block, but it does deny Black the plan ...Na6 and ...Nc7. The ...b5 break is
the key to Black's counterplay, and now it will be harder to achieve.} ({
In the next couple of games, we examine} 6... Bd7) ({and} 6... Nfd7 {.}) 7. a4
(7. O-O $6 {doesn't make sense, since Black's reply either forces ...b5 or
makes White cough up the bishop pair:} a6 8. Bxd7+ Nxd7 {when Black looks good
with a bishop pair and some freedom due to the last exchange, D.Balko-V.Vodicka, Tatranske Matliare 2007.}) 7... O-O 8. O-O a6 9. Be2 Rb8 ({Instead,} 
9... b6 {stops a5. The plan is to slowly prepare the ...b5 break, but after}
10. Re1 Ne8 11. Bf4 Nc7 12. Qd2 Rb8 13. Bh6 b5 14. Bf1 b4 15. Nd1 a5 16. Bxg7
Kxg7 17. Ne3 {it was advantage White in B.Abramovic-L.Popov, Stara Pazova 2007,
who controls c4 and has essentially closed off the queenside, Black's realm of
counterplay. Moreover, Black's dark-squared defender has been eliminated and
White may build for a kingside attack, with Black's only chance for
counterplay being to engineer a timely ...e6 break.}) 10. Re1 ({
Tal isn't attracted to the strategic plan} 10. a5 {and plays directly for mate.
}) 10... Ne8 11. Bf4 Nc7 {Last chance for White to throw in a5.} 12. Bf1 $5 {
Sorry, not interested.} b5 13. Qd2 $5 ({Avoiding} 13. axb5 Nxb5 14. Nxb5 axb5
15. c3 {which reduces the number of attackers.}) 13... Re8 14. h3 Nf6 $1 {
A subtle and instructive move. Black returns the merchandise to the store for
a full refund. The knight retraces its steps to f6, its work done on d7: -- 1.
A knight on f6 puts more heat on d5, which inhibits White from his planned e5
pawn break; and -- 2. Benko knows his opponent! He adds a defender to his king
to prepare for the coming storm.} 15. Rad1 Bd7 16. e5 $5 {
What the ...!? I really don't understand the mind of an absolute tactician.} ({
Why didn't Tal simply throw in} 16. axb5 {first before the e5 pawn break? Why
does he give up a pawn on the queenside? Sorry about all these questions. I
realize that the annotator is supposed to offer answers not annoy the reader
with questions. But really, I don't get it!}) 16... b4 $1 {
